'''''The Secret of Monkey Island''''' is a {{vgy|1990}} [[Graphic adventure game#Point-and-click adventure|point-and-click graphic adventure game]] developed and published by [[Lucasfilm Games]]. It takes place in a fantastical version of the [[Caribbean]] during the age of [[Piracy in the Caribbean|piracy]]. The player assumes the role of [[Guybrush Threepwood]], a young man who dreams of becoming a pirate and explores fictional islands while solving puzzles. 

The game was conceived in 1988 by Lucasfilm employee [[Ron Gilbert]], who designed it with [[Tim Schafer]] and [[Dave Grossman (game developer)|Dave Grossman]]. Gilbert's frustrations with contemporary adventure titles led him to make the [[player character]]'s death impossible, which meant that gameplay focused the game on exploration. The atmosphere was based on that of the [[Pirates of the Caribbean (attraction)|Pirates of the Caribbean]] theme park ride. ''The Secret of Monkey Island'' was the fifth game built with the [[SCUMM]] engine, which was heavily modified to include a more user-friendly interface.

Critics praised ''The Secret of Monkey Island'' for its humor, audiovisuals, and gameplay. The game spawned a number of sequels, collectively known as the [[Monkey Island series|''Monkey Island'' series]]. Gilbert, Schafer and Grossman also led the development of the sequel ''[[Monkey Island 2: LeChuck's Revenge]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamasutra.com/view/feature/4070/back_in_the_water_the_monkey_.php?print=1|title=Back in the Water: The Monkey Island Interview|date=July 6, 2009|author=Chris Remo|publisher=[[Gamasutra]]|accessdate=December 10, 2010}}</ref> LucasArts released a remake of the original in 2009, which was also well received by the gaming press.

==Gameplay==
''The Secret of Monkey Island'' is a [[2D computer graphics|2D]] [[adventure game]] played from a [[Third person (video games)|third-person perspective]]. Via a [[point-and-click]] interface, the player guides protagonist Guybrush Threepwood through the game's world and interacts with the environment by selecting from twelve verb commands (nine in newer versions) such as "talk to" for communicating with characters and "pick up" for collecting items between commands and the world's objects in order to successfully solve puzzles and thus progress in the game.<ref name="IGNFondMem">{{cite web|url=http://retro.ign.com/articles/909/909836p1.html|title=Fond Memories: The Secret of Monkey Island|first=Levi|last=Buchanan|date=September 12, 2008|accessdate=November 26, 2011|publisher=[[IGN]]}}</ref> While conversing with other characters, the player may choose between topics for discussion that are listed in a [[dialog tree]]; the game is one of the first to incorporate such a system.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamasutra.com/view/news/29696/Analysis_Smooth_Talk__The_Evolution_Of_Dialog_Trees.php|title=Analysis: Smooth Talk <U+2013> The Evolution Of Dialog Trees|first=Jeffrey|last=Matulef|date=August 5, 2010|accessdate=November 26, 2011|publisher=[[Gamasutra]]}}</ref> The in-game action is frequently interrupted by [[cutscene]]s, [[Interactivity|non-interactive]] animated sequences that are used to provide information about character personalities and advance the plot.<ref>{{cite manual|author=Shepard, Mark|title=The Secret of Monkey Island Manual|page=5|publisher=[[Lucasfilm Games]]|date=October 1990}}</ref> Like other [[LucasArts adventure games]], ''The Secret of Monkey Island'' features a design philosophy that makes the player character's death nearly impossible (Guybrush does drown if he stays underwater for more than ten minutes).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.1up.com/do/feature?pager.offset=0&cId=3167594|title=Game Over: Tension and the tentacle|first=Evan|last=Shamoon|date=April/May 2008|accessdate=November 26, 2011|publisher=[[Games for Windows: The Official Magazine]]}}</ref>

==Plot==
{{see also|World of Monkey Island}}

A youth named Guybrush Threepwood arrives on the fictional M<U+00EA>l<U+00E9>e Island, with the desire to become a pirate. He seeks out the island's pirate leaders, who set him three trials that must be completed to become a pirate: winning a [[duel|sword duel]] against Carla, the island's resident swordmaster, [[treasure hunt|finding a buried treasure]], and stealing a valuable idol from the governor's mansion.<ref name="VG">{{cite video game|title=The Secret of Monkey Island|developer=[[Lucasfilm Games]]|platform=[[DOS]]|date=October 1990}}</ref> These quests take Guybrush throughout the island, where he hears of stories of the Ghost Pirate [[LeChuck]], who apparently died in an expedition to the mysterious Monkey Island, an act that was meant to win the love of the governor [[Elaine Marley]].<ref name="VG" /> Guybrush meets several characters of interest, including a [[World of Monkey Island#Voodoo Lady|local voodoo priestess]], [[World of Monkey Island#Stan|Stan the Used Boat Salesman]], a prisoner named Otis, and Meathook, whose hands have been replaced by hooks.

Guybrush also encounters the governor and is instantly smitten, and she soon reciprocates. However, as he completes the tasks set for him, the island is raided by LeChuck and his undead crew, who abduct Elaine and then retreat to their secret hideout on Monkey Island.<ref name="VG" /> Guybrush takes it upon himself to rescue her, buying a ship and hiring Carla, Otis, and Meathook as crew before setting sail for the fabled island. When Guybrush reaches Monkey Island, he discovers a village of [[cannibal]]s in a dispute with [[World of Monkey Island#Herman Toothrot|Herman Toothrot]], a ragged [[castaway]] marooned there. He settles their quarrel, and then recovers a magical "voodoo root" from LeChuck's ship for the cannibals, who provide him with a [[Soda syphon|seltzer bottle]] of "voodoo root elixir" that can destroy ghosts.<ref name="VG" /> 

When Guybrush returns to LeChuck's ship with the elixir, he learns that LeChuck has returned to M<U+00EA>l<U+00E9>e Island to marry Elaine at the church. He promptly returns to M<U+00EA>l<U+00E9>e Island and gatecrashes the wedding, only to ruin Elaine's own plan for escape; in the process he loses the elixir.<ref name="VG" /> Now confronted with a furious LeChuck, Guybrush is savagely beaten by the ghost pirate in a fight ranging across the island. The fight eventually arrives at the island's ship emporium, where Guybrush finds a bottle of [[root beer]]. Substituting the beverage for the lost elixir, he sprays LeChuck, destroying the ghost pirate. With LeChuck defeated, Guybrush and Elaine enjoy a romantic moment, watching fireworks caused by LeChuck exploding.<ref name="VG" />

==Development==
===Origin and writing===
[[Ron Gilbert]] conceived the idea of a pirate adventure game in 1988, after completing ''[[Zak McKracken and the Alien Mindbenders]]''.<ref name="RGInt">{{cite journal|date=December 5, 2008|title=The Making Of <U+2013> The Secret of Monkey Island|journal=[[Retro Gamer]]|issue=34|pages=58<U+2013>61|publisher=[[Imagine Publishing]]}}</ref> He first wrote story ideas about pirates while spending the weekend at a friend's house. Gilbert experimented with introductory paragraphs to find a satisfactory idea. His initial story featured unnamed villains that would eventually become LeChuck and Elaine; Guybrush was absent at this point.<ref name="RG-70">{{cite journal|magazine=Retro Gamer|publisher=Imagine Publishing|issue=70|title=Tales from Monkey Island|pages=29<U+2013>35| first=Ashley|last=Day|year=2009}}</ref> He pitched it to [[Lucasfilm Games]]'s staff as a series of short stories.<ref name="AdvInt">{{cite journal|year=Fall 1990|title=The Secret of Creating Monkey Island|journal=Lucasfilm Adventurer|volume= 1|issue= 1|publisher=[[Lucasfilm Games]]|url=http://www.scummbar.com/resources/articles/index.php?newssniffer=readarticle&article=1033}}</ref> Gilbert's idea was warmly received, but production was postponed because Lucasfilm Games assigned its designers, including Gilbert, to ''[[Indiana Jones and the Last Crusade: The Graphic Adventure]]''.<ref name="RGInt"/> Development of ''The Last Crusade'' was finished in 1989, which allowed Gilbert to begin production of ''The Secret of Monkey Island'', then known internally under the working title ''Mutiny on Monkey Island''.<ref name="RGInt"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamespot.com/xbox360/adventure/sesame-street-once-upon-a-monster/video/6313423|title=Video Game History Month: Tim Schafer|date=May 12, 2011|publisher=[[GameSpot]]|accessdate=November 15, 2011}}</ref>

[[File:RonGilbert 2011 adjusted.jpg|thumb|upright|left|alt=A brown haired man in a gray shirt looks into the camera while standing against black background.|[[Ron Gilbert]] led the game's development and conceived its plot (2011 photo).]]

Gilbert soon realised that it would be difficult to design the game by himself; he decided to join forces with [[Tim Schafer]] and [[Dave Grossman (game developer)|Dave Grossman]], both of whom he hired for Lucasfilm.<ref name="DThreads">{{cite web|url=http://www.gamespot.com/features/6153188/designer-threads-feat-ron-gilbert-6-30-06/p-2.html|title=Designer Threads Featuring Ron Gilbert <U+2013> Part 2|date=June 30, 2006|author=[[Greg Kasavin]]|publisher=[[GameSpot]]|accessdate=November 15, 2011}}</ref> The game's insult swordfighting mechanics were influenced by swashbuckling movies starring [[Errol Flynn]], which Gilbert, Schafer and Grossman often watched for inspiration. They noticed that pirates in those films often taunted their opponents instead of attacking them, which gave the designers the idea to base the game's duels on insults rather than combat.<ref name="RGInt"/><ref name="GG1">{{cite web|url=http://grumpygamer.com/8280380|title=Stuff and Things and Monkey Island|date=June 1, 2009|author=[[Ron Gilbert]]|publisher=[[Grumpy Gamer]]|accessdate=November 15, 2011}}</ref> Writer [[Orson Scott Card]] helped them write the insults during a visit to Lucasfilms' headquarters at [[Skywalker Ranch]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamefront.com/gaming-todays-exclusive-interview-with-author-orson-scott-card/|title=Gaming Today<U+2019>s Exclusive Interview with Author Orson Scott Card|first=Ron|last=Whittaker|date=June 15, 2007|publisher=[[GameFront]]|accessdate=November 15, 2011}}</ref> Many of Gilbert's original gameplay ideas were abandoned during the production process, although he stated that "most of that stuff was left out for a reason".<ref name="GG1"/>

{{double image|right|Tim Schafer 2011.jpg|140|Dave Grossman - 920448657 - barret.jpg|200|[[Tim Schafer]] (left, 2011 photo) and [[Dave Grossman (game developer)|Dave Grossman]] (right, 2007 photo) co-wrote the game's plot with Gilbert and supplied programming.||A Caucasian man in green jacket looks into the camera. He is standing against black background.|A man wearing multicolored shirt smiles at the camera. Behind him stands a blue and white background, above which is an excerpt of logo which reads "games".}}

The game's plot, as described by Dave Grossman: <U+201C>It<U+2019>s a story about this young man who comes to an island in search of his life<U+2019>s dream. He<U+2019>s pursuing his career goals and he discovers love in the process and winds up thinking that was actually more important than what he was doing to begin with. You<U+2019>re laughing, but there<U+2019>s actually something deeper going on as well.<U+201D><ref name="MSNBC">{{cite web|url=http://www.msnbc.msn.com/id/31942046/ns/technology_and_science-games/t/aye-matey-beloved-pirate-games-set-sail-again/#.TqATupuBo8k|title=Aye matey, beloved pirate games set sail again|date=July 7, 2009|author=Winda Benedetti|publisher=[[MSNBC]]|accessdate=November 15, 2011}}</ref> When work on the plot began, Gilbert discovered that Schafer's and Grossman's writing styles were too different to form a cohesive whole: Grossman's was "very kind of a dry, sarcastic humor" and Schafer's was "just a little more in your face". In reaction, Gilbert assigned them to different characters and story moments depending on what type of comedy was required.<ref name="DThreads"/> Grossman believed that this benefited the game's writing, as he and Schafer "were all funny in slightly different ways, and it worked well together".<ref name="MSNBC"/> Schafer and Grossman wrote most of the dialogue while they were programming the game; as a result, much of it was improvised.<ref name="RGInt"/> Some of the dialogue was based on the designers' personal experiences, such as Guybrush's line "I had a feeling in hell there would be mushrooms", which came from Schafer's own hatred of fungi.<ref name="GG1"/> 

The game's world and characters were designed primarily by Gilbert. After having read [[Tim Powers]]' historical fantasy novel ''[[On Stranger Tides]]'', he decided to add [[paranormal]] themes to the game's plot. He also cited Powers' book as an influence on the characters, particularly those of Guybrush and LeChuck. Inspiration for the game's ambiance came from Gilbert's favorite childhood amusement park ride, [[Pirates of the Caribbean (attraction)|Pirates of the Caribbean]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://grumpygamer.com/6476640|title=On Stranger Tides|date=September 20, 2004|author=[[Ron Gilbert]]|publisher=[[Grumpy Gamer]]|accessdate=November 15, 2011}}</ref> Grossman said that Gilbert always wanted "to step off the ride" and "talk to the people who lived in that world".<ref name="MSNBC"/> Near the final stages of the design work, Gilbert introduced several characters who were not directly related to the game's story. He considered this to be an important decision, as the player would need those seemingly minor characters in later parts of the game and would receive a chance to "really interact with them".<ref name="AdvInt"/> The developers included a character from ''[[Loom (video game)|Loom]]'' (another 1990 LucasArts title). When approached for conversation, the character (Cobb) encourages the player to purchase ''Loom''.<ref name="WAT-Remake">{{cite web| url=http://blogs.watoday.com.au/digital-life/screenplay/2009/06/18/bygeorgeitsm.html|title=By George, it's Monkey magic|publisher =[[WAtoday]]|first=Jason|last=Hill|date=June 18, 2009|accessdate=June 21, 2009}}</ref>

===Creative and technical design===
Gilbert, Schafer and Grossman's primary goal was to create a simpler and more accessible gameplay model than those presented in previous Lucasfilm titles. Gilbert had conceived the main designs and puzzles before production began, which resulted in the bulk of the designers' work to flesh out his ideas.<ref name="RGInt"/> He was frustrated by the adventure games that [[Sierra On-Line]] was releasing at the time, and later said that "you died any time you did anything wrong". Gilbert considered such gameplay as "a cheap way out for the designer".<ref name="RGInt"/> He had previously applied his design ideas to the 1987 graphic adventure title ''[[Maniac Mansion]]'', but committed a number of mistakes during development, such as dead end situations that prevented the player from completing the game and poorly implemented triggers for cutscenes. Gilbert aimed to avoid such errors in ''The Secret of Monkey Island''.<ref name="GamesTm-Retro">{{cite journal|magazine=[[GamesTM]]|publisher=[[Imagine Publishing]]|location=Bournemouth|title=Behind the Scenes: ''Maniac Mansion'' + ''Day of the Tentacle''|year=2010 |issue=3|pages=22<U+2013>27|series=''The Ultimate Retro Companion''|issn=1448-2606|oclc=173412381}}</ref> The team decided to make it impossible for the player character to die, which focused gameplay primarily on world exploration.<ref name="RGInt"/>  

{{Multiple image|direction=vertical|align=right|image1=The Secret of Monkey Island SCUMM Bar.jpg|image2=The Secret of Monkey Island Special Edition SCUMM Bar.jpg|width=230|caption1=A scene in The Secret of Monkey Island shows the protagonist Guybrush Threepwood standing on the docks of M<U+00EA>l<U+00E9>e Island. Below the scene, the game displays the list of the verb commands and items in the player's inventory in a point-and-click menu.|caption2=The same scene in the special edition. The verb portion of the screen has been removed as part of a control overhaul, while the background artwork has been made more elaborate to build a more vibrant environment.}}

''The Secret of Monkey Island'' was the fifth Lucasfilm Games project powered by the [[SCUMM]] engine, originally developed for ''Maniac Mansion''. The company had gradually modified the engine since its creation.<ref name="GamesTm-Retro">{{cite journal| magazine=[[GamesTM]]|publisher=[[Imagine Publishing]]|title=Hall of Fame: Guybrush Threepwood|year=2010|issue=3 |pages=188<U+2013>189| series=The Ultimate Retro Companion|issn=1448-2606|oclc=173412381}}</ref> For ''Maniac Mansion'', the developers [[Hard coding|hard coded]] verb commands in the SCUMM scripting language. These commands become more abstract in subsequent versions of the engine. The developers carried over the practice of referring to individual segments of the gameworld as "rooms", even though the areas in ''Monkey Island'' were outdoors.<ref name="GDC-Post">{{cite web|url=http://www.gdcvault.com/play/1014732/Classic-Game-Postmortem-MANIAC|last=Gilbert|first=Ron|title=Classic Game Postmortem: ''Maniac Mansion''|publisher=[[Game Developers Conference]]|format=Flash Video|date=March 4, 2011|accessdate=March 23, 2011}}</ref> The game uses the same version of the engine used in ''Indiana Jones and the Last Crusade'', with minor changes. A [[dialog tree]] was added, which facilitated conversation options and the sword-fighting puzzles.<ref name="GamesTm-Retro"/> The developers removed the "What is" option (an input command that describes an on-screen object to the player) in favor of allowing the player to simply highlight the object with the mouse cursor.<ref name="GamesTm-Retro"/><ref name="AdvG">{{cite web|url=http://www.adventuregamers.com/article/id,808|title=Adventure Gamers's Top 20 <U+2013> #2: The Secret of Monkey Island|date=April 2, 2004|author=Evan Dickens|publisher=[[Adventure Gamers]]|accessdate=November 15, 2011}}</ref> The game's improved interface became the standard for the company's later titles. The game also introduced logical verb shortcuts, which could be performed with the mouse; for example, clicking on a character defaults to the "talk" action, the most obvious action in the situation.<ref name="AdvG"/> SCUMM's visuals were updated for the game<U+2014>the original [[Enhanced Graphics Adapter|EGA]] version had a 320x200&nbsp;pixel resolution rendered in 16&nbsp;colors.<ref name="GDC-Post"/><ref name="Spud-Stone-Monkey">{{cite web|url=http://spudvisionblog.blogspot.com/2011/02/stone-monkey-head.html|title=A Stone Monkey Head|date=February 22, 2011|publisher=Spudvision|accessdate=November 15, 2011}}</ref> According to artist [[Steve Purcell]], that became a major limitation for the art team; due to a low number of "ghastly" colors, they often chose bizarre tones for backgrounds.<ref name="Spud-Stone-Monkey"/> They chose black and white for Guybrush's outfit for the same reason.<ref name="GamesTm-Retro"/> The [[Video Graphics Array|VGA]] version of the game later corrected these issues by implementing 256 color support, which allowed for more advanced background and character art.<ref name="AdvG"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mobygames.com/game/dos/secret-of-monkey-island/screenshots/gameShotId,318376/|title=The Secret of Monkey Island <U+2013> Screenshot 26 of 40|date=August 13, 2008|publisher=[[MobyGames]]}}</ref>

The game's "pirate [[reggae]]" music was composed by Lucasfilm Games' in-house musician [[Michael Land]] in [[MIDI]] format. It was his first project at the company.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gsoundtracks.com/interviews/land.htm|title=GSoundtracks <U+2013> Interview with composer Michael Land|publisher=GSoundtracks|accessdate=November 15, 2011}}</ref> The game was originally released for [[floppy disk]] in 1990, but a [[CD-ROM]] version with a high-quality CD soundtrack followed in 1992.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://allgame.com/game.php?id=36583|title=The Secret of Monkey Island (CD-ROM)|publisher=[[Allgame]]}}</ref> The music has remained popular, and has been remixed by the musicians of [[OverClocked ReMix]] and by the game's fans.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ocremix.org/game/212/secret-of-monkey-island-dos|title=Game: The Secret of Monkey Island|publisher=[[OverClocked ReMix]]|accessdate=November 15, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://scummbar.com/tx/games/music/|title=The Secret of Monkey Island <U+2013> MP3 Downloads|publisher=scummbar.com|accessdate=November 15, 2011}}</ref>

===Special Edition===
LucasArts released a remake with updated audiovisuals titled ''The Secret of Monkey Island: Special Edition'' in July 2009 for [[iPhone]], [[Microsoft Windows]], and [[Xbox 360]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamespot.com/iphone/adventure/thesecretofmonkeyislandspecialedition/tech_info.html|title=The Secret of Monkey Island: Special Edition Tech Info|publisher=[[GameSpot]]|accessdate=November 15, 2011}}</ref> exclusively via download.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://xboxlive.ign.com/articles/990/990254p1.html|title=E3 2009: The Secret of Monkey Island: Special Edition Preview|date=June 2, 2009|first=Charles|last= Onyett|publisher=[[IGN]]|accessdate=November 15, 2011}}</ref> [[PlayStation 3]], [[Mac OS]] and [[iPad]] versions followed early in 2010 for download on their respective services.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mobygames.com/game/secret-of-monkey-island-special-edition/release-info|title=The Secret of Monkey Island: Special Edition release info|publisher=[[MobyGames]]|accessdate= November 15, 2011}}</ref> LucasArts confirmed the game's development on June 1, 2009; rumors appeared several days earlier when the Xbox 360 version of the game received an [[USK]] rating.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://xboxlive.ign.com/articles/988/988553p1.html|title=E3 2009: Monkey Island XBLA Official|publisher=[[IGN]]|author=Daemon Hatfield|date=June 1, 2009|accessdate=November 15, 2011}}</ref> The game was first displayed to the public at the 2009 [[Electronic Entertainment Expo|E3]] in June.<ref name="GSPE3"/> The remake features hand-drawn visuals with more detail, a remastered musical score, voice work for characters, and a hint system. The developers included the function to switch between 2009 and original audiovisuals at will.<ref name="GSPE3">{{cite web|url=http://www.gamespot.com/the-secret-of-monkey-island-special-edition/previews/the-secret-of-monkey-island-special-edition-impressions-new-graphics-new-music-plus-a-history-lesson-6211077/|title=The Secret of Monkey Island Special Edition Impressions <U+2013> New Graphics, New Music, Plus a History Lesson|last=Park|first=Andrew|work=[[GameSpot]] ([[CBS Interactive]])|date=June 2, 2009|accessdate=November 15, 2011}}</ref><ref name="GSPInt">{{cite web|url=http://www.gamespot.com/the-secret-of-monkey-island-special-edition/previews/the-secret-of-monkey-island-special-edition-first-look-6210601/|title=The Secret of Monkey Island Special Edition First Look|work=[[GameSpot]] ([[CBS Interactive]])|last=Tong|first=Sophia|date=June 1, 2009|accessdate=November 15, 2011}}</ref> The voice actors included Dominic Armato as Guybrush Threepwood and Earl Boen as LeChuck; most had provided voice work in sequels to ''The Secret of Monkey Island''.<ref name="WAT-Remake"/>

LucasArts's game producer Craig Derrick and his team conceived the idea of the remake in 2008.<ref name="GSPInt"/> After researching the [[Monkey Island (series)|''Monkey Island'' series]]' history, they decided to make "something fresh and new while staying true to the original", which resulted in the idea of ''The Secret of Monkey Island'''s remake.<ref name="GSPInt"/> The developers tried to leave much of the original design unchanged. Any changes were intended to achieve the level of immersion desired for the original. To that end, they added details like a pirate ship or pirates talking in the background of scenes. While the team considered the SCUMM interface revolutionary at the time, LucasArts community manager Brooks Brown noted that it is incompatible with an analog stick, which most consoles use. The designers made the cursor contextual to the game objects as the primary interface. Brown had considered updating the reference to advertise ''[[Star Wars: The Force Unleashed]]'' because ''Loom'' was not on the market at the time, but concluded that the game would not be the same if such changes were implemented.<ref name="WAT-Remake"/> Prior to the ''Special Edition'' release, however, LucasArts announced that ''Loom'', along with other games from its back catalog, would be made available on [[Steam (software)|Steam]].<ref>{{cite press release|url= http://www.lucasarts.com/company/release/news20090706.html|title=Back by Popular Demand, LOOM, The Dig, Indiana Jones and the Fate of Atlantis, and Star Wars Battlefront II Headline List of Games Soon to be Available via Direct Download!|publisher= LucasArts|date=July 6, 2009|accessdate=November 16, 2011}}</ref> Brown stated that the decision to distribute the game online was because "digital downloads have finally gotten going".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://xbox360.ign.com/articles/996/996023p1.html|title=Interview: Monkey Island <U+2013> The Return of Adventure Games|publisher=[[IGN]] Australia|date=June 17, 2009|author=Patrick Kolan|accessdate=November 15, 2011}}</ref>
