|rev7=''[[ACE (games magazine)|ACE]]''
|rev7Score=922 (Amiga)<br>918 (Atari ST)<br>915 (IBM PC)<ref name=ace>{{cite journal|last=Cooke|first=Steve|title=''The Secret of Monkey Island''|issue=46|date=July 1991|journal=[[ACE (games magazine)|ACE]]|pages=76, 77}}</ref>
|rev8 = ''[[Mega (magazine)|Mega]]''
|rev8Score = 91%<ref>[[Mega (magazine)|Mega]] review, issue 6, page 33, March 1993</ref>
}}
''The Secret of Monkey Island'' received positive reviews from critics. Hartley, Patricia, and Kirk Lesser of ''[[Dragon (magazine)|Dragon]]'' praised the designers' attention to detail, and cited the game's humor as a high point. Although they believed that the game was too expensive, they summarized it as "a highly enjoyable graphic adventure replete with interesting puzzles, a fantastic [[Roland Sound Canvas|Roland]] soundtrack, superb [[Video Graphics Array|VGA]] graphics, smooth-scrolling animation, and some of the funniest lines ever seen on your computer screen."<ref name=dragon /> Duncan MacDonald of ''[[Zero (video game magazine)|Zero]]'' praised the graphics and found the game "quite amusing". His favorite aspect was the fine-tuned difficulty level, which he believed was "just right". He ended his review, "At last an adventure game that's enjoyable rather than frustrating."<ref name=zero/> Paul Glancey of ''[[Computer and Video Games]]'' consider the game superior to Lucasfilm's earlier adventure titles, and wrote that, "Usually the entertainment you get from an adventure is derived solely from solving puzzles, but the hilarious characters and situations, and the movie-like presentation ... make playing this more like taking part in a comedy film, so it's much more enjoyable." He considered the puzzles to be "brilliantly conceived" and found the game's controls accessible. He summarized it as "utterly enthralling".<ref name=cvg/><ref name=amigapower/>

''[[ACE (games magazine)|ACE]]''{{'}}s Steve Cooke also found the controls convenient, and he praised the game's atmosphere. He wrote that, "in graphics and sound terms ... ''Monkey Island'', along with ''[[King's Quest V]]'', is currently at the head of the pack." However, he disliked the designers' running joke of placing "TM" after character and place names, which he thought detracted from the atmosphere. He singled out the game's writing, characters and plot structure as its best elements.<ref name= ace/> ''[[Amiga Power]]''{{'}}s Mark Ramshaw wrote, "With ''The Secret of Monkey Island'', the mouse-controlled, graphic-adventure comes of age." He lauded its comedic elements, which he believed were the highlight of the game. The reviewer also praised the control scheme, noting that it allows the player to "more or less forget about the specifics of what [they are] physically doing ... and lose [themselves] in the adventure instead." He noted that the game's plot and visual and aural presentation fit together to create a thick atmosphere, and finished, "Forget all those other milestone adventures (''[[Zork]]'', ''[[The Hobbit (1982 video game)|The Hobbit]]'', ''[[Lord of the Rings: Game One|Lord of the Rings]]'' ''et al'') <U+2014> for sheer enjoyment and general all-round perfection, ''The Secret of Monkey Island'' creams 'em all in style."<ref name=amigapower /> The game, along with its sequel, was ranked the 19th best game of all time by ''Amiga Power''.<ref>Amiga Power magazine issue 64, Future Publishing, August 1996</ref>

Writing for ''[[The One (magazine)|The One]]'', Paul Presley stated that "Lucasfilm appears to have taken all of the elements that worked in its previous releases and, not only incorporated them into this tale of scurvy swashbuckling, but even improved on them in the process!" Like the other reviewers, he praised its controls. He also lauded its "hilarious storyline, strong characters and ... intriguing setting", but complained about graphical slowdowns.<ref name=theone/> Nick Clarkson of ''[[Amiga Computing]]'' cited the game's graphics as "flawless", noting that "the characters are superbly animated and the backdrops simply ooze atmosphere." He highly praised its sound effects and music, and believed that its controls "couldn't be simpler".<ref name=amigacomputing /> The staff of ''[[Amiga Action]]'' wrote that the "attention to detail and the finely tuned gameplay cannot be faulted." They called the graphics "stunning throughout", and believed that, when they were combined with the "excellent Caribbean tunes", the result is a game filled with "character and atmosphere." They ended by stating that "there is absolutely no excuse for not owning this game."<ref name=amigaaction/>

''The Secret of Monkey Island'' has featured regularly in lists of "top" games, such as ''[[Computer Gaming World]]'s'' Hall of Fame<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.1up.com/do/feature?pager.offset=6&cId=3139081#54|title=CGW's Hall of Fame|publisher=[[1UP.com]]}}</ref> and [[IGN]]'s Video Game Hall of Fame.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://games.ign.com/halloffame/secret-of-monkey-island.html|title=IGN Videogame Hall Of Fame: The Secret of Monkey Island|publisher=IGN|year=2007|accessdate=December 21, 2011}}</ref> In 1996, ''Computer Gaming World'' ranked it as the 19th best game of all time, "writing "Who could ever forget the insult-driven duel system or the identity of the mysterious Swordmaster?".<ref>''CGW'' 148: 150 Best Games of All Time</ref> In 2010, IGN ranked the Xbox Live Arcade version as the 20th best title of all time for that platform.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://xboxlive.ign.com/articles/112/1120887p1.html|title=The Top 25 Xbox Live Arcade Games|publisher =[[IGN]]|date=16 September 2010|accessdate=2010-09-16 }}</ref> In 2009, IGN named ''The Secret of Monkey Island'' one of the ten best [[LucasArts adventure games]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pc.ign.com/articles/104/1046144p1.html|title=Top 10 LucasArts Adventure Games|publisher=IGN|date=November 17, 2009|accessdate=November 18, 2011}}</ref>

===2009 re-release===
{{Video game reviews
|IGN=8.7 out of 10<ref name=ign2>{{cite web|last=Hatfield|first=Daemon|date=July 14, 2009|url=http://xboxlive.ign.com/articles/100/1003651p1.html|title=''The Secret of Monkey Island: Special Edition'' Review|work=[[IGN]]|accessdate=December 13, 2011}}</ref>
|EuroG=9 out of 10<ref name=eurogamer/>
|GSpot=8 out of 10<ref name=gamespot2/>
|GamePro=4 out of 5<ref name=gamepro>{{cite web|last=Ely|first=Sean|date=July 21, 2009|title=PC/XBLA Review <U+2013> ''The Secret of Monkey Island: Special Edition''|work=[[GamePro]]|archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20100922015733/http://gparcade.blogfaction.com/article/109307/pc-xbla-review-the-secret-of-monkey-island-special-edition/| url=http://gparcade.blogfaction.com/article/109307/pc-xbla-review-the-secret-of-monkey-island-special-edition/| archivedate=August 22, 2010}}</ref>
}}

Like the original release, ''The Secret of Monkey Island: Special Edition'' received positive reviews from critics. Sean Ely of ''[[GamePro]]'' praised its updated audio, and said that the new graphics "blow the old clunker visuals ... out of the water". He cited its script, humor, plot, puzzles and balanced difficulty level as high points, and finished, "''The Secret of Monkey Island: Special Edition'' is impressive, hilarious and downright worth your money."<ref name=gamepro/> Daemon Hatfield of [[IGN]] wrote, "Almost 20 years after its release, [''The Secret of Monkey Island''] remains a blast to play." He called the new graphics "slick, if a little generic", and noted that the "original graphics have a certain charm to them that the fancy pants new visuals just don't." However, he enjoyed the redone music, the new hint function, and the added sound effects and voice acting. He summarized it as "one of the best times you'll ever have pointing and clicking", and noted that "few games are this funny."<ref name=ign2 /> Justin Calvert of [[GameSpot]] noted that "the Special Edition looks much better and is the only way to play if you want to hear ... what characters are saying, whereas the original game's interface is less clunky." However, he wrote that "the voice work is such a great addition to the game that it's difficult to go back to the original edition." He praised its humor, writing, puzzles and characters, and he believed that it had aged well.<ref name=gamespot2>{{cite web|last=Calvert|first=Justin|date=April 23, 2010|title=''The Secret of Monkey Island: Special Edition'' Review|url=http://www.gamespot.com/the-secret-of-monkey-island-special-edition/reviews/the-secret-of-monkey-island-special-edition-review-6260007|work=[[GameSpot]]|accessdate=December 15, 2011 }}</ref> [[Eurogamer]]'s Dan Whitehead wrote, "Purists like me will almost certainly find something to grumble about over the span of the game, but the overall impact of the redesign is undeniably for the better." However, he preferred the original game's Guybrush design, and believed that the new control system was "rather less intuitive" than the old one. He finished by stating that "few games can stand the test of time with such confidence".<ref name=eurogamer>{{cite web|last=Whitehead|first=Dan|date=July 15, 2009|title=''Secret of Monkey Island: Special Edition'' Review|url=http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/the-secret-of-monkey-island-special-edition-review|work=[[Eurogamer]]|accessdate=December 15, 2011}}</ref>

==Legacy==
{{See also|Monkey Island (series)}}

''The Secret of Monkey Island'' spawned four sequels. The first, ''[[Monkey Island 2: LeChuck's Revenge]]'', was released in 1991 and focuses on LeChuck's return.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.joystiq.com/2010/11/18/ron-gilbert-digs-up-treasure-in-the-form-of-monkey-island-2-bug/|title=Ron Gilbert digs up treasure in the form of Monkey Island 2 bug reports|first=JC|last=Fletcher|date=November 18, 2010|publisher=[[Joystiq]]|accessdate=November 24, 2011}}</ref> Six years later, LucasArts released ''[[The Curse of Monkey Island]]'', which features a new visual design.<ref>{{cite press release|url=http://www.thefreelibrary.com/Shiver+Me+Timbers!+LeChuck's+Back+and+He's+Deader+Than+Ever+in...-a018655836|title=Shiver Me Timbers! LeChuck's Back and He's Deader Than Ever in LucasArts' Swashbuckling Monkey Island Series Sequel, The Curse of Monkey Island; Salty Humor, Exotic Locales and Ghost Pirates Galore Highlight Latest Chapter of Award-Winning High-Sea Adventure.|date=September 9, 1996|publisher=[[Business Wire]]|accessdate=November 24, 2011}}</ref> In 2000, the company released ''[[Escape from Monkey Island]]'', which uses the [[GrimE]] engine of ''[[Grim Fandango]]'' to produce 3D graphics.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamespot.com/escape-from-monkey-island/reviews/escape-from-monkey-island-review-2652023?page=2|title=Escape from Monkey Island Review <U+2013> Page 2|first=Ron|last=Dulin|date=November 9, 2000|publisher=[[GameSpot]]|accessdate=November 24, 2011}}</ref> The next title, ''[[Tales of Monkey Island]]'' released in 2009, is a series of five [[Episodic video game|episodic chapters]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.shacknews.com/article/58892/tales-of-monkey-island-announced|title=Tales of Monkey Island Announced, Secret of Monkey Island to Be Revamped|first=Alice|last=O'Connor|date=June 1, 2009|publisher=[[Shacknews]]|accessdate=November 24, 2011}}</ref>

Elements of the game have appeared elsewhere in popular culture. In 2005, student Chris Heady wrote, directed, and produced a live stage version of ''The Secret of Monkey Island'' at [[Hammond High School (Columbia, Maryland)|Hammond High School]] in Columbia, Maryland. LucasArts licensed the play for a year, but stipulated that the script be used for nonprofit purposes and could not be distributed outside cast and crew.<ref name="BaltSun">{{cite web|url=http://articles.baltimoresun.com/2005-04-29/news/0504290101_1_hammond-high-heady-lucasarts|title=Pirates and a villain will roam the stage|publisher=[[The Baltimore Sun]]| date=April 29, 2005|first=Dana|last=Klosner-Wehner|accessdate=November 16, 2011}}</ref> The adaptation resulted in [[Guinness World Records]] awarding the game a record for the "first graphic adventure to become a stage play".<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.guinnessworldrecords.com/records-6000/first-graphic-adventure-to-become-a-stage-play/|title=First graphic adventure to become a stage play|publisher=[[Jim Pattison Group]]|work=Guinness World Records|accessdate=November 16, 2011}}</ref> 
Also, the original version was selected as one of five for the exhibition ''The Art of Video Games'' in the [[Smithsonian American Art Museum]] in 2011.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.americanart.si.edu/exhibitions/archive/2012/games/|publisher=[[Smithsonian American Art Museum]]|year=2011|accessdate=2011-07-31|title=Exhibitions: The Art of Video Games|quote=''Five games will be available for visitors to play for a few minutes, to gain some feel for the interactivity<U+2014> [[Pac-Man]], [[Super Mario Brothers]], The Secret of Monkey Island, [[Myst]], and [[World of Warcraft]].''}}</ref>

A fictional drink recipe in the game for [[grog]] was mistakenly reported as real in 2009 by Argentinian news channel C5N, which urged teenagers not to consume the dangerous Grog XD drink.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://kotaku.com/5348907/argentine-tv-warns-world-of-monkey-islands-grog-recipe|title=Argentine TV Warns World of Monkey Island's Grog Recipe&nbsp;<U+2014> fail|publisher=Kotaku|first =Owen|last=Good|date=30 August 2009|accessdate=2010-04-11}}</ref> In ''[[Tales of Monkey Island]]'', Guybrush refers to this news story while pushing the Grog XD button on a Grog machine.<ref>{{cite video game|title=Tales of Monkey Island: "Rise of the Pirate God"|developer=Telltale Games|date=December 2009|platform=PC|quote='''Guybrush:''' Grog XD. This must be that new high-energy grog that all the kids are drinking these days. It's sold out. Which is fine by me, the kerosene and battery acid tend to keep me up at night.}}</ref>

